articularly in the form of heroines—has a rich history in film in the years just prior to the American entry into World War I. The American Girl Goes to War demonstrates the predominance of heroic female characters in in early narrative films about war from 1908 to 1919. American Girls were filled with the military spirit of their forefathers and became one of the major ways that American women’s changing political involvement, independence, and active natures were contained by and subsumed into pre-existing American ideologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHeroines in motion picturesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex role in motion picturesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSilent filmszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar filmszUnited StatesxHIstory and criticism. 0aWomen and warzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in motion picturesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica, film, war, media studies, communications, military, history, popular culture, gender, national identity, silent film, protagonist, heroine, politics, independence, femininity, Civil War, wartime, gender roles, social norms, World War I.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881019840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978810198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978810198/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK